node.text: Now here’s an absolute monster of a wave from @afonsobandagarra that is oh so worthy of recognition. Speaking of which, @nicvonrupp and his company @thebrusco have launched their #bruscochargerofthemonth comp, awarding the winner with a pack of surf goodies. “Our whole idea was to give credit and recognition to those underground chargers that constantly search for the best and heaviest waves in the Atlantic Ocean,” said Nic. “We want to inspire people to push their limits and there is no better example than these guys that put their lives on the line only for the pure love of surfing. This inspires me everyday and I believe it will also inspire the younger generations.” We couldn’t have said it better. Head over to the site for a full run down of this session and some insight from Afonso. Vid @vanlife_productions

node.text: Time for a 2-5 minute edit? Think most of us have these days. Every Friday, we'll be dropping one of our exclusive edits striaght to IG. First up, this session from deepest Cornwall in February of last year. The day before, the south west had been dripped by a blizzard, freezing over the roads and making travel damn near impossible. But a lucky crew managed to make the journey, hinderance free, and were greeted by a few barrels off this reefbreak. Featuring @alan_stokes @skindoggydog and many more, all shot by @biskit_bodyboarding you can find the full feature on the site, just search Cornwall in our shiny new nav bar.

Join @lukedavisthegrey for a tour across this fine land, link in bio.

node.text: UPDATE: Hurricane Larry is sending swell up the US east coast. Larry will then track up to Greenland, potentially sending a long-range and long period pulse towards Europe. What that means for the beachies? Well, it could mean lulls between sets and you’ll need to find somewhere with a decent bank to break up the swell. And yeah, it’s hard to know where the banks are decent because the surf’s been so flat for some parts of Europe. Ireland though…But, as always, we’ll keep you updated and the latest forecast is in the link in bio.

node.text: Hurricane Larry could be on the way to the UK and Europe. And with it comes a long, 18 second swell period, which could be good or bad depending on where you are in the world and what type of break your local is. Pic 1 Nazare from @helio_antonio, pic 2) Shows swell period broken down, ie how a longer-period wave (left) feels the bottom, but a shorter-period wave in the same depth of water (right) doesn’t. Hit the link in bio for more and to learn why swell period is important for forecasting.
